SIMPLE: odds
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Odds
<hw>Odds</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧dz)</pr>, <pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Odd</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Difference in favor
of one and against another; excess of one of two things or numbers over
the other; inequality; advantage; superiority; hence, excess of chances;
probability. The odds are often expressed by a ratio; <as>as, the
<ex>odds</ex> are three to one that he will win, i. e. he will win three
times out of four</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Preeminent by so much
<xex>odds</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧The fearful
<xex>odds</xex> of that unequal fray.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Trench.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>odds</qex>⟦br⟧
Is that we scarce are men and you are gods.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There appeared, at least, four to one <qex>odds</qex> against
them.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the <qex>odds</qex> between them has been the different scope
. . . given to their understandings to range in.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Judging is balancing an account and determining on which side the
<qex>odds</qex> lie.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Quarrel; dispute; debate; strife; -- chiefly in the
phrase <xex>at odds</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Set them into confounding <qex>odds</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I can not speak⟦br⟧
Any beginning to this peevish <qex>odds</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At odds</b></col>, <cd>in dispute; at variance.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧These squires <xex>at odds</xex> did fall.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Spenser.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧He flashes into one gross crime or other, that
sets us all <xex>at odds</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>It is
odds</b></col>, <cd>it is probable; same as <cref>odds are</cref>, but
no longer used.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Jer. Taylor.</au> --
<col><b>odds are</b></col> <cd>it is probable; <as>as, <ex>odds are</ex>
he will win the gold medal</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Odds and
ends</b></col>, <cd>that which is left; remnants; fragments; refuse;
scraps; miscellaneous articles.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧My brain is filled . . .
with all kinds of <xex>odds and ends</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>W. Irving.</au>
-- <col><b>slim odds</b></col> <cd>low odds; poor chances; <as>as, there
are <ex>slim odds</ex> he will win any medal</as>.</cd> </cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ode</ent>⟦br⟧
